{
  "The Net Change Theorem states that the integral from a to b of F'(x) dx equals:": "",
  "F'(b) - F'(a)": "",
  "F(b) - F(a)": "",
  "F(a) + F(b)": "",
  "F(a) - F(b)": "",
  "The Net Change Theorem says integral from a to b of F'(x) dx = F(b) - F(a). The integral of a rate of change gives the total (net) change in the original quantity. This is a direct consequence of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.": "",
  "If v(t) = 6t - 12 is the velocity of a particle, the net displacement from t = 0 to t = 4 is:": "",
  "0": "",
  "-4": "",
  "Net displacement = integral from 0 to 4 of (6t - 12) dt = [3t^2 - 12t] from 0 to 4 = (48 - 48) - 0 = 0.": "",
  "If a tank fills at a rate of r(t) = 10 - 2t gallons per minute, how many gallons are added from t = 0 to t = 5?": "",
  "10 gallons": "",
  "25 gallons": "",
  "50 gallons": "",
  "0 gallons": "",
  "Net change = integral from 0 to 5 of (10 - 2t) dt = [10t - t^2] from 0 to 5 = 50 - 25 = 25 gallons.": "",
  "The total distance traveled by a particle with velocity v(t) = t^2 - 4 from t = 0 to t = 3 is found by:": "",
  "integral from 0 to 3 of (t^2 - 4) dt": "",
  "|integral from 0 to 3 of (t^2 - 4) dt|": "",
  "integral from 0 to 3 of (t^2 - 4)^2 dt": "",
  "integral from 0 to 3 of |t^2 - 4| dt": "",
  "Total distance requires integrating the absolute value of velocity: integral of |v(t)| dt. This accounts for direction changes (when the particle reverses). The velocity changes sign at t = 2, so the integral must be split there.": "",
  "If the population growth rate is P'(t) = 100*e^(0.02t) people per year and P(0) = 5000, then P(10) =": "",
  "5000 + 5000(e^(0.2) - 1)": "",
  "6000": "",
  "5000 + 1000": "",
  "5000*e^(0.2)": "",
  "P(10) = P(0) + integral from 0 to 10 of 100*e^(0.02t) dt = 5000 + 100[50*e^(0.02t)] from 0 to 10 = 5000 + 5000(e^(0.2) - 1).": "",
  "Water flows into a reservoir at rate R_in(t) = 20 + 3t gal/hr and flows out at rate R_out(t) = 15 gal/hr. The net change in water volume over 6 hours is:": "",
  "30 gallons": "",
  "84 gallons": "",
  "174 gallons": "",
  "54 gallons": "",
  "Net rate = R_in - R_out = (20 + 3t) - 15 = 5 + 3t. Net change = integral from 0 to 6 of (5 + 3t) dt = [5t + 3t^2/2] from 0 to 6 = 30 + 54 = 84 gallons.": "",
  "If f'(x) = 2x + 1 and f(0) = 3, then f(4) =": "",
  "23": "",
  "20": "",
  "16": "",
  "19": "",
  "f(4) = f(0) + integral from 0 to 4 of (2x + 1) dx = 3 + [x^2 + x] from 0 to 4 = 3 + (16 + 4) = 23.": "",
  "The acceleration of a car is a(t) = 6 m/s^2 (constant). If v(0) = 10 m/s, what is the velocity at t = 5?": "",
  "80 m/s": "",
  "40 m/s": "",
  "60 m/s": "",
  "30 m/s": "",
  "v(5) = v(0) + integral from 0 to 5 of 6 dt = 10 + 6(5) = 10 + 30 = 40 m/s.": "",
  "An accumulation function is defined as g(x) = integral from 0 to x of f(t) dt. Then g'(x) =": "",
  "integral from 0 to x of f'(t) dt": "",
  "f(x)": "",
  "f'(x)": "",
  "f(0)": "",
  "By the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (Part 1), if g(x) = integral from a to x of f(t) dt, then g'(x) = f(x). The derivative of the accumulation function equals the integrand evaluated at the upper limit.": "",
  "If the rate of change of a quantity Q is dQ/dt = -3t + 12, and Q(0) = 50, at what time does Q reach its maximum?": "",
  "t = 8": "",
  "t = 6": "",
  "t = 2": "",
  "t = 4": "",
  "Q is maximized when dQ/dt = 0: -3t + 12 = 0, giving t = 4. Since dQ/dt goes from positive (for t < 4) to negative (for t > 4), t = 4 is indeed a maximum.": "",
  "What is the 'Net Change Theorem'?": "",
  "The derivative of a function gives the net change": "",
  "The sum of all positive changes minus all negative changes": "",
  "A method for computing average values": "",
  "The integral of a rate of change over an interval gives the total net change in the original quantity": "",
  "The Net Change Theorem states that integral from a to b of F'(x) dx = F(b) - F(a). In other words, integrating the rate of change of a quantity over an interval yields the total (net) change in that quantity over that interval.": "",
  "What does 'accumulation function' mean?": "",
  "A function defined as the integral from a fixed point to a variable upper limit: g(x) = integral from a to x of f(t) dt": "",
  "A function whose derivative is zero without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The sum of a sequence, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual accumulation mechanisms at work": "",
  "A function that always increases when considering all relevant accumulation factors": "",
  "An accumulation function g(x) = integral from a to x of f(t) dt represents the total accumulated value of f from a fixed starting point a up to x. By FTC Part 1, its derivative is g'(x) = f(x), connecting integration and differentiation.": "",
  "What is 'net displacement' vs. 'total distance'?": "",
  "Total distance is the derivative of displacement, as conventional displacement theory would suggest": "",
  "Net displacement is the integral of velocity (accounting for direction); total distance is the integral of the absolute value of velocity": "",
  "Net displacement is always greater than total distance regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "They are the same thing, since standard models of displacement behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Net displacement = integral of v(t) dt (can be positive, negative, or zero, as it accounts for direction). Total distance = integral of |v(t)| dt (always non-negative, counting all movement regardless of direction). Total distance >= |net displacement|.": "",
  "What does 'rate of change' mean in the context of the Net Change Theorem?": "",
  "The total amount accumulated": "",
  "The derivative of a quantity with respect to time or another variable": "",
  "The difference between maximum and minimum values": "",
  "The average of a quantity": "",
  "A rate of change is the derivative of a quantity, describing how fast that quantity changes per unit of the independent variable. Examples include velocity (rate of change of position), growth rate (rate of change of population), and flow rate (rate of change of volume).": "",
  "What does 'initial value problem' mean?": "",
  "A problem where you know the derivative and an initial condition, and you find the original function": "",
  "Finding the first value of a sequence": "",
  "Computing the derivative at the starting point": "",
  "A problem that has no solution": "",
  "An initial value problem (IVP) provides a differential equation (the rate of change) along with a known starting value. Using the Net Change Theorem, the solution is F(x) = F(a) + integral from a to x of F'(t) dt.": "",
  "What does 'flow rate' mean in accumulation problems?": "",
  "The pressure of the fluid": "",
  "The speed of the fluid": "",
  "The total volume of fluid in a container": "",
  "The volume of fluid passing a point per unit time": "",
  "Flow rate measures the volume of fluid passing through a point per unit time (e.g., gallons per minute or liters per second). Integrating flow rate over time gives the total volume that has flowed: V = integral of R(t) dt.": "",
  "What is the 'Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, Part 1'?": "",
  "Every function has an antiderivative": "",
  "The integral of a sum equals the sum of the integrals": "",
  "If g(x) = integral from a to x of f(t) dt where f is continuous, then g'(x) = f(x)": "",
  "The derivative of a constant is zero": "",
  "FTC Part 1 states that if f is continuous on [a, b] and g(x) = integral from a to x of f(t) dt, then g is differentiable and g'(x) = f(x). This theorem establishes that differentiation and integration are inverse processes.": "",
  "What does 'signed area' mean?": "",
  "Area of a region with a signature label": "",
  "Area that is always positive": "",
  "Area counted as positive above the x-axis and negative below the x-axis": "",
  "Half the total area": "",
  "Signed area is the area computed by a definite integral, where regions above the x-axis contribute positive area and regions below the x-axis contribute negative area. The definite integral gives the net signed area.": "",
  "What does 'Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, Part 2' state?": "",
  "If F is an antiderivative of f on [a, b], then the integral from a to b of f(x) dx = F(b) - F(a)": "",
  "Every continuous function has a unique antiderivative": "",
  "The integral of f'(x) equals f(x)": "",
  "Integration and differentiation cancel each other exactly": "",
  "FTC Part 2 (also called the Evaluation Theorem) states that if F is any antiderivative of f on [a, b], then integral from a to b of f(x) dx = F(b) - F(a). This provides the practical method for evaluating definite integrals.": "",
  "What does 'net change' mean in the context of integration?": "",
  "The largest single change, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing change dynamics": "",
  "The total change in a quantity, found by integrating its rate of change, with increases and decreases offsetting each other": "",
  "The change at the endpoint only under most circumstances involving change": "",
  "The absolute value of all changes when considering all relevant change factors": "",
  "Net change is the difference F(b) - F(a), which accounts for both increases and decreases in the quantity. For example, if an account gains $100 then loses $40, the net change is $60. It is found by integrating the rate of change over the interval.": "",
  "A factory's production rate is P(t) = 100 + 10*sin(pi*t/12) units per hour. How many units are produced in a 24-hour day?": "",
  "2400 units": "",
  "2640 units": "",
  "2520 units": "",
  "2160 units": "",
  "Total = integral from 0 to 24 of [100 + 10*sin(pi*t/12)] dt = [100t - 10*(12/pi)*cos(pi*t/12)] from 0 to 24. The cosine term evaluates to -(120/pi)[cos(2*pi) - cos(0)] = -(120/pi)(1 - 1) = 0. So total = 2400 units.": "",
  "A water tank starts with 500 gallons. Water flows in at rate R_in(t) = 30 gal/min and leaks out at R_out(t) = 5 + 2t gal/min. After how many minutes is the tank fullest?": "",
  "10 minutes": "",
  "15 minutes": "",
  "6 minutes": "",
  "12.5 minutes": "",
  "Net rate = 30 - (5 + 2t) = 25 - 2t. The tank is fullest when net rate = 0: 25 - 2t = 0, so t = 12.5 minutes. Before this time, water flows in faster than it leaks; after this time, it leaks faster.": "",
  "A car's velocity is v(t) = 60 - 6t mph. The car starts at mile marker 10. At what mile marker is the car at t = 5 hours?": "",
  "Mile marker 160": "",
  "Mile marker 235": "",
  "Mile marker 310": "",
  "Mile marker 85": "",
  "Position at t = 5: s(5) = 10 + integral from 0 to 5 of (60 - 6t) dt = 10 + [60t - 3t^2] from 0 to 5 = 10 + (300 - 75) = 10 + 225 = 235. The car is at mile marker 235.": "",
  "An online store's revenue grows at a rate of R'(t) = 2000*e^(0.05t) dollars per month. If the initial cumulative revenue is $0, what is the total revenue after 12 months?": "",
  "40,000 dollars": "",
  "24,000*e^(0.6) dollars": "",
  "40,000(e^(0.6) - 1) dollars": "",
  "2000*12 dollars": "",
  "Total revenue = integral from 0 to 12 of 2000*e^(0.05t) dt = 2000[20*e^(0.05t)] from 0 to 12 = 40,000(e^(0.6) - 1) dollars.": "",
  "A battery discharges at a rate of I(t) = 5*e^(-0.1t) amps. If the battery starts with 50 coulombs of charge, how much charge remains after 10 seconds?": "",
  "50 - 50(1 - e^(-1)) coulombs": "",
  "0 coulombs": "",
  "50 - 5 coulombs": "",
  "50*e^(-1) coulombs": "",
  "Charge lost = integral from 0 to 10 of 5*e^(-0.1t) dt = 5[-10*e^(-0.1t)] from 0 to 10 = -50(e^(-1) - 1) = 50(1 - e^(-1)). Remaining charge = 50 - 50(1 - e^(-1)) = 50*e^(-1) = approximately 18.4 coulombs. Both the first and second options are equivalent: 50 - 50(1 - e^(-1)) = 50e^(-1).": "",
  "A glacier melts at a rate of M(t) = 200 + 15t cubic meters per year, where t is years from now. How much ice is lost in the next 10 years?": "",
  "2000 cubic meters": "",
  "3250 cubic meters": "",
  "2750 cubic meters": "",
  "3500 cubic meters": "",
  "Total melt = integral from 0 to 10 of (200 + 15t) dt = [200t + 15t^2/2] from 0 to 10 = 2000 + 750 = 2750 cubic meters.": "",
  "A jogger's velocity is v(t) = 8 - 2t m/s for 0 <= t <= 6 seconds. What are the net displacement and total distance traveled?": "",
  "Net displacement = 20 m, Total distance = 20 m": "",
  "Net displacement = 0 m, Total distance = 20 m": "",
  "Net displacement = 12 m, Total distance = 20 m": "",
  "Net displacement = 12 m, Total distance = 12 m": "",
  "v(t) = 0 at t = 4. Net displacement = integral from 0 to 6 of (8 - 2t) dt = [8t - t^2] from 0 to 6 = 48 - 36 = 12 m. Total distance = integral from 0 to 4 of (8 - 2t) dt + integral from 4 to 6 of |8 - 2t| dt = [8t - t^2] from 0 to 4 + [t^2 - 8t] from 4 to 6 = 16 + |(36 - 48) - (16 - 32)| = 16 + |(-12) - (-16)| = 16 + 4 = 20 m.": "",
  "A hospital admits patients at a rate of A(t) = 10 + 3*cos(pi*t/12) patients per hour and discharges at rate D(t) = 8 patients per hour. Starting with 200 patients, how many patients are in the hospital after 24 hours?": "",
  "272": "",
  "248": "",
  "200": "",
  "224": "",
  "Net rate = (10 + 3*cos(pi*t/12)) - 8 = 2 + 3*cos(pi*t/12). Net change = integral from 0 to 24 of [2 + 3*cos(pi*t/12)] dt = [2t + 3*(12/pi)*sin(pi*t/12)] from 0 to 24 = 48 + (36/pi)(sin(2pi) - sin(0)) = 48 + 0 = 48. Total = 200 + 48 = 248 patients.": "",
  "A rocket burns fuel at rate r(t) = 50*e^(-0.02t) kg/s. If the rocket starts with 3000 kg of fuel, how much fuel remains after 30 seconds?": "",
  "3000 - 2500(1 - e^(-0.6)) kg": "",
  "3000 - 1500 kg": "",
  "3000*e^(-0.6) kg": "",
  "1500 kg": "",
  "Fuel burned = integral from 0 to 30 of 50*e^(-0.02t) dt = 50[-50*e^(-0.02t)] from 0 to 30 = -2500(e^(-0.6) - 1) = 2500(1 - e^(-0.6)). Remaining = 3000 - 2500(1 - e^(-0.6)) kg.": "",
  "A city's electricity demand varies as D(t) = 500 + 200*sin(pi*t/12) MW, where t is hours past midnight. The power supply is constant at 600 MW. During which hours does demand exceed supply?": "",
  "When sin(pi*t/12) > 0.5, i.e., approximately from t = 2 to t = 10": "",
  "From t = 2 to t = 10 (approximately 2 AM to 10 AM)": "",
  "Demand never exceeds supply": "",
  "From t = 6 to t = 18 (6 AM to 6 PM)": "",
  "Demand > supply when 500 + 200*sin(pi*t/12) > 600, i.e., sin(pi*t/12) > 0.5. This occurs when pi*t/12 is in (pi/6, 5*pi/6), giving t in (2, 10). So demand exceeds supply approximately from 2 AM to 10 AM.": ""
